{"title_page": "Kuchesar Fort", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n[[File:Mud_Fort_Kuchesar.jpg|thumb|Mud Fort Kuchesar]]\n'''Kuchesar (\u0915\u0941\u091a\u0947\u0938\u0930) Fort''', also known as the '''Mud Fort, was built in 1734 as an [[opium]] trading depot of [[Uttar Pradesh, India]]. Several royal heirs stayed in Kuchesar Fort as a means of furthering profits, and therefore, increasing the trading depot's popularity. Eventually, government officials closed it down due to a significant number of [[Death|deaths]] and [[Disease|illnesses]]. Many theorized that the plants that grew over the building were responsible for the \"unhealthy environment\". Recently, the locals of [[Kuchesar]] took the initiative to clear away the foliage. In 1994, the fort was restored, and turned into a hotel, it is now known as the \"Mud Fort Kuchesar\". It has become a popular tourist attraction for the city.\n\n==History==\nKuchesar Fort belonged to the Dalal clan of Jats. It was the seat of Jat Princely estates at [[Kuchesar]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsFarEast/IndiaJatsMinorKings.htm|title=Kingdoms of South Asia - Minor Indian Kingdoms of the Jats|website=www.historyfiles.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> during the [[Mughal Empire]], and [[British Raj]]. The [[Jat people]] competed with [[Maratha]]s, [[Rohilla|Rohillas]], French colonists, traders and explorers, as well as the [[British East India Company]]: after the decline of the [[Mughal Empire]]. Kuchesar Fort was also a center for the Rai Brahmins, also called Bhatts (a branch of [[Kashmiri Brahmins]]). They were the Rajkavi of Kuchesar State (Rajkavis: are similar to [[Poet laureate|poets laureate]]). Rai Moti Bhatt was the final Rajkavi of Kuchesar State.\n\nThe rulers of Kuchesar built the fort in 1734 and maintained state population awareness records. The fort was granted to Ramdhan Singh's family on a perpetual lease by a Mughal Emperor named [[Shah Alam II]] in 1790. This grant was confirmed by the [[British Raj|British]] in 1807. Ajit Singh's family acquired Kuchesar Fort during the 18th century. When the [[Najib ad-Dawlah]] bestowed the Jat family with title of [[Rao Bahadur]] (Rai Bahadur).  The fort served as seat of the estates for Jat Kingdom of Uttar Pradesh.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Restoration and present-day operations==\nThe fort was restored, then turned into a heritage-style hotel in 1994. The founding family still occupies a portion of the hotel. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldarchitecture.org/architecture-projects/cphn/kuchesar_mud_fort_as_a_heritage_hotel-project-pages.html|title=Kuchesar Mud Fort, as a Heritage Hotel|website=worldarchitecture.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>  \n\nScenes from the 2017 Indian film [[The Hungry]], starring [[Naseeruddin Shah]] and [[Tisca Chopra]] were filmed here.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/india-s-women-directors-make-a-mark-at-toronto-film-fest/story-M3YayfKigcFZ04steJu3JN.html|title=India\u2019s women directors make a mark at Toronto film fest|website=hindustantimes.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links ==\n\n* [http://www.mudfortkuchesar.com/ Kuchesar Fort, website]\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Kuchesar}}\n\n{{coord missing|Uttar Pradesh}}[https://www.google.com/maps/place/Kuchesar+Road+Chaupala,+Uttar+Pradesh+245201,+India/@28.7461979,77.9085697,15z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x390c827b3e85ba1d:0x4e07830dd899bfe5!8m2!3d28.7445054!4d77.91755 Google map location]\n\n{{Forts in India}}\n{{Forts in Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Forts in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Heritage hotels in India]]\n[[Category:Bulandshahr district]]\n[[Category:18th-century establishments in India]]\n[[Category:18th-century forts in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n[[File:Mud_Fort_Kuchesar